  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute cross-border money laundering\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Risk-based approaches to monitoring financial activities\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align their national laws with international frameworks\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar legal mechanisms for asset seizure and prosecution\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Blacklisting of non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Economic pressure to adopt robust AML frameworks\n\n6. Technology and Information Sharing\n- Global databases tracking suspicious financial activities\n- Collaborative digital platforms for investigating financial crimes\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to combating money laundering internationally.",
